The first $14$ terms of the sequence are $1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 11, 12, 13, 15, 16, 17.$  Notice that there are $3$ terms between $1^2 = 1$ and $2^2 = 4,$ $4$ terms between $2^2 = 4$ and $3^2 = 9,$ and so on.

We want the $200$th term of the sequence.  If we include the perfect squares, then the first $14$ perfect squares give us $14$ terms, the next $12$ perfect squares give us $24$ terms, the next $10$ perfect squares give us $20$ terms, and so on.  We want the smallest integer $n$ such that
\[14 + 24 + 20 + \dots + 2n \ge 200.\]Simplifying the left-hand side gives us $n^2 + n - 28 \ge 0.$  The roots of $n^2 + n - 28 = 0$ are $n = -1 \pm \sqrt{29},$ so the smallest such positive integer is $\boxed{5}.$

